ed net energy production yet.  The dense plasma focus may not have yields that are higher than the scaling law, despite Lerner's hypothesis that the DPF can have similar pinching phenomena as that which occurs in quasars. Even if they overcome their current issues with impurities in the vacuum chamber, if they can't achieve yields that scale much more than the current scaling law of DPF's (which they haven't), then it would require a larger reactor than what they predict, even the size of ITER or a tokamak. Then again, even if a very large reactor is required, the electricity generation could be converted directly from a beam of charged particles rather than via a significantly more expensive steam turbine. On the other hand, if a large reactor is required, the disadvantage of that is that centralised energy generally has more drawbacks than distributed energy, e.g. more network augmentation required, less ability for end users of electricity to be empowered (pun intended) and decentralised energy trading is not available. 展开Steven Marsh · 2015年9月28日I think this is a valid path for Scientific inquiry because I have personally used Plasma to vaporize steel! Also, I think that for Humans to be able to move on... from an economic system that rewards the domination of resources and exploitation of political systems, that we desperately need an energy system like this.  If it works, then great, if it doesn't then we will have learned a great deal from this and the other experimental approaches being tried, and we must try them all.  In the meantime, there are lots of awesome investment opportunities in Shared/Public Transit and existing renewable energy technologies that we must (and are) pursuing, so despite the disconcerting nature of the changes that we are experiencing, the future is bright indeed.  To me, the single most important thing that I look forward to, is the possibility that, at last, we will have achieved an economic system that rewards innovation instead 